…Says Anyone Caught Sharing Video Of Underage Pupil Risk 14 Years Imprisonment The Lagos State Government, has reacted to the alleged sexual assault case of the 10-year-old Chrisland pupil whose video of her performing an immoral act with male classmates was seen on the Internet by shutting down the school till further notice. According to a statement jointly signed by the Ministry of Education, Office of Education Quality Assurance, Ministry of Youth and Social Development, Ministry of Justice Lagos State Domestic and Sexual Violence Agency, anyone who shares the video on social media is liable to custodial sentence of fourteen (14) years. The statement reads, “The attention of the Lagos State Government has been drawn to the alleged sexual violence. “ It is pertinent to note that all allegations ore being investigated by the relevant Ministries, Departments and Agencies, including Ministry of Education, Office of Education Quality Assurance, Ministry of Youth and Social Development, Ministry of Justice and the Lagos State Domestic & Sexual Violence Agency, whilst the criminal allegations have been escalated to the Commissioner of Police. “In view of the allegations, we are committed to ensuring that adequate medical and pscyho social support is provided. “This is to reassure members of the public of the State Government’s commitment to safety and child protection, especiolly in ensuring that all child-centered institutions within the state, formulate and implement policies and systems that are compliant with the Executive Order (NO.E0/AA08 of 2016), Logos State Safeguarding and Child Protection Program. “We also use this medium to remind the general public on the implications pertaining to engaging in any visual depiction of sexually explicit conduct involving of a child commits an offence and is liable to custodial sentence of fourteen (14) years. This includes “producing, distributing, receiving, or possessing an image of child pornography”. POLL “In the meantime, all Chrisland schools within Logos State are hereby closed, pending further investigations.”